==English==
===Noun===
'''chaser''' (''plural'' '''chasers''')

#A person who chases.
##One who chases women, a woman-chaser
#A drink
##A drink of [[spirit]]s drunk after another drink.
##A non-alcoholic drink consumed immediately after drinking a potent liquor to dull the harsh taste of alcohol.
#A small, light, usually single-seated aeroplane of great speed and climbing power, used in repelling hostile aircraft
#A ship which chases another
#In the form [[wikipedia:bow chaser|bow chaser]] or [[wikipedia:stern chaser|stern chaser]], naval cannons pointing forward or aft and used in ship chases
#A piece of music played or an inferior [[vaudeville]] act or motion picture presented to induce an audience to leave
#Someone that follows logs out of the forest in order to signal a [[yarder engineer]] to stop them if they become fouled -- also called a <span style="font-variant:small-caps;text-transform:lowercase">[[frogger]]</span>
#A horse trained for [[wikipedia:steeplechase (horse racing)|steeple-chasing]]
#A ram that has only one testicle
#A tool used for cutting the threads of screws
#One of the [[wikipedia:edge-wheels|edge-wheels]] which revolves in a [[trough]], to grind substances to powder
#(1990s) ''slang:'' A frequent user of [[wikipedia:crack-cocaine|crack-cocaine]]
#''slang:'' A prison guard
#(''Harry Potter''; ''always capitalised'') A field position in the game [[Quidditch]].

